There’s a lot of great reasons why daily tummy time is essential for baby’s development, one of the best is practicing and getting proficient at head turning side to side. 

Head turning side to side is a REFLEX for babies, but only when they are in tummy time! Reflexes are movements that happen because the right sensory input came in. Tummy time is a big part of sensory input, development and processing for babies. 

Babies are building the foundation of MOVEMENT and SENSORY PROCESSING in tummy time, for the rest of their lives! 

Does your little one turn their head side to side easily in tummy time? If not, let’s work on it together 💜

Many babies appear to HATE tummy time, but that’s just the outer layer and not baby’s truth 

Tummy time is an essential element for baby’s neurodevelopment, nervous system, strength, endurance, posture, GI function, sensory processing, movement skills and lots more. 

Tummy time is the natural way human babies develop!

Baby’s brain and sensory processing skills actually SEEK tummy time experiences, however, because we have cultural barriers to tummy time, many babies do not get early or adequate doses or exposure to help baby find the joy in this position 

Yes, tummy time can be challenging! That’s the whole point.  Babies develop best with the just right challenge and this is what TummyTime! Method is all about

Lack of Experience
Nervous System Dysregulation

Quadruped is another term for the hands and knees, ready to crawl position and is an essential aspect in human development. 

Transitioning from tummy time on the floor to pushing up on extended arms and knees is a major change in developmental skill, strength, balance and coordination!

Imagine using the floor to support your whole body in tummy time and that changing to having only your hands and knees/ lower legs on the surface!  This is a big deal 🙌🏽

Quadruped itself is a skill and it also leads to crawling!

Rolling is a fun developmental skill and babies do it all kinds of ways. 

This is the common seen head directed roll where the body follows. 

Babies become quite proficient at repeating this! 

Rolling from tummy to back typically happens around 3-6 months, depending on the baby’s individual development and maturation. 

Rolling isn’t a great marker of development necessarily, because it happens in such a wide range 

Rolling is a a cool part of sensory processing and whole body mobility!

We don’t really need research to tell us tummy time and crawling are good for baby’s health and wellness, but it’s nice to see when it helps us understand the IMPORTANCE of how the brain learns in infancy and the effects later in life. 

This study shows us that ACTIVELY engaging in crawling or a cognitive task lights up the prefrontal cortex of the brain whereas being pushed in a stroller or watching a screen did not. 

This doesn’t mean don’t use strollers! We use them when we need them, but also make sure baby get lots of opportunities for activity and free movement on the floor. 

Additionally, spending time playing with your baby lights up the prefrontal cortex as well, whereas screen or passive activities do not. 

What did you find interesting about this study?

One of the activities babies do in tummy time is head turning side to side. 

These important movements develop baby’s:

⭐️ Head control 

⭐️ Neck Movement

⭐️ Vision and Visual Tracking

Rotating the head back and forth so mobilize tongue and the throat which improve feeding and swallowing, as well!

Babies are able to turn their head side to side very early after birth and are quite capable by 2-3 weeks old when they get enough practice !

Does tummy time LAST FOREVER?!?!

When we break it down, the tummy time period doesn’t last that long ! 

It’s really less than 5 or 6 months in total, and after that babies prefer and enjoy the position and are moving around and preparing to crawl, if not, already crawling.

Hang in there and be confident that your daily practice helps a lot! 

This sweet and important short period of development sets the foundation for baby’s posture, balance and whole body movement for life!

These short tummy time days are well worth it ⭐️

During the age range of 5-6 months and up, babies start using big powerful movements that strengthen their spine and ensure good posture for life!

A big part of that is the Landau reflex that initiates baby’s head, arms and legs lifting up strongly off the surface.  This is imperative for a straight spine !

Babies at this age also push up on their arms and hands and even rock forward and backward with big ranges of motion. 

These movements are important and so is ENJOYING IT!! 

Neurodevelopmental maturation is amazing and requires lots of powerful movements !

Since the mid 90s, most of the medical providers around the globe have followed the #backtosleep recommendations 

Prior to this, babies slept on their tummies, spending roughly half their lives in this position receiving the benefits. 

Medical professionals knew back sleeping would have a negative impact on development, so they also developed the #tummytoplay campaign at the same time as back to sleep.  The problem is the tummy to play part gets a lot less attention and respect.

Intentional tummy time during the day, offsets the time babies spend sleeping on their backs. 

One of the biggest and most important developmental achievements in the first 6 months is posture and the foundation for whole body coordination and postural control. 

Don’t listen to anyone telling you that daily, intentional tummy time isn’t necessary for your baby in a back to sleep culture!! 

if your baby needs help and support enjoying tummy time and engaging in it successfully, consider a #TeleTummiesVirtualConsult with a TTM professional.  It’s an easy and affordable way to help your little one get all the tummy time benefits ⭐️⭐️⭐️♥️

Posture begins to develop the moment baby is born as their nervous system is getting used to moving in the gravity field.  This is a dramatic difference from the fluid filled womb, for movement and postural reflexes!

One of the most salient reasons for tummy time in the first 12 to 16 weeks of life, is how the brain and nervous system interact with gravity to move the head and body to the upright position. 

This is challenging as baby’s head is the heaviest part of the body! 

These are developmentally appropriate activities, challenging the brain and stimulating optimal neurodevelopment!

This is an exciting point for me as an OT working to optimize baby’s health, posture, movement and connection!

Good sleep is essential for optimal health and neurodevelopment and this is true for babies too!

Clinically we have appreciated the connection between. Tummy time and good sleep, but it’s always nice when the research backs it up!

And….. there’s a probable connection between doing tummy time effectively and SLEEP for babies found in the research !

A recent study looked at the effects of tummy time on sleep and found that when compared to babies who do 1 hour of tummy time a day, babies who did less 

🚩 slept less 

🚩 had worse sleep efficiency

🚩 had shorter sleep duration 

🚩 and more night awakenings

There’s more research to do to prove the link, but it’s a good start at finding the benefits of tummy time beyond physical developmental milestones!

Crawling that starts at birth is referred to as the #breastcrawl and is a reflex all human babies have for survival and connection.  It ONLY happens when babies are placed on their tummies tho!  The tummy time position elicits the crawling reflex. 

Babies can locomote / crawl all the way from the lower belly to the breast when this reflex is working well. 

This instinctual crawling lasts a few weeks so if you didn’t get a chance to do this right after birth, you can still offer these experiences for baby within this time period. 

Regular crawling comes later, around 6-9 months, but this first type of crawling is special and deserves some recognition!

Why is the crawling reflex so important? It stimulates oral feeding and whole body responses that OPTIMIZE feeding skills, alertness levels, strength, tone and whole body movements!

TummyTime is a great way to address Head Shape issues. 

Many babies experience head molding or flattening such as 

🚩Plagiocephaly - typically one side is flat in the other side is a little bulgy

🚩Brachycephaly typically the back of the head is flat, and there can be a little bulge on both sides

🚩 Scaphocephaly the head has a narrow shape and is a bit flattened on both sides

While tummy time isn’t the only way to address head and body shape issues, it’s one of the top positive contributors to shape changes for babies! 

Tummy time optimizes cranial nerve function which increases: 

✅ Tongue function and swallowing 

✅ Jaw position and movement 

✅ Head and postural control 

✅ Mobility and locomotion 

plus a lot more

Tummy time is essential for postural development, especially in a back to sleep culture. 

Postural control supports all developmental movements, both gross and fine motor !

Gross motor are big movements and fine motor are smaller, more refined movements and include reaching, manipulating and playing with toys etc 

Mastery of reaching and manipulation relies on adequate postural control. The trunk must be balanced relative to a base of support to allow free movements of the arms and hand

Fine motor skills rely on posture as much as gross motor skills, so let’s do some tummy time today to get ready to PLAY!
